"Wilson L.J., Hald M., Godtliebsen F.","Foraminiferal faunal evidence of twentieth-century Barents Sea warming",2011,"Holocene","21","4",,"527","537",,,10.1177/0959683610385718,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79957656015&partnerID=40&md5=c4b43c07b2b7375804e590e959285403","Institutt for geologi, Universitetet i Tromsø, Dramsveien 201, N-9037 Tromsø, Norway; Institutt for matematikk og statistikk, Universitetet i Tromsø, Norway","Wilson, L.J., Institutt for geologi, Universitetet i Tromsø, Dramsveien 201, N-9037 Tromsø, Norway; Hald, M., Institutt for geologi, Universitetet i Tromsø, Dramsveien 201, N-9037 Tromsø, Norway; Godtliebsen, F., Institutt for matematikk og statistikk, Universitetet i Tromsø, Norway","Instrumental monitoring of the climate at high northern latitudes has documented the ongoing warming of the last few decades. Climate modelling has also demonstrated that the global warming signal will be amplified in the polar region. Such temperature increases would have important implications on the ecosystem and biota of the Barents Sea. This study therefore aims to reconstruct the climatic changes of the Barents Sea based on benthic foraminifera over approximately the last 1400 years at the decadal to sub-decadal scale. Oxygen and carbon isotope analysis and benthic foraminiferal species counts indicate an overall warming trend of approximately 2.6°C through the 1400-year record. In addition, the well-documented cooling period equating to the 'Little Ice Age' is evident between c. 1650 and 1850. Most notably, a series of highly fluctuating temperatures are observed over the last century. An increase of 1.5°C is shown across this period. Thus for the first time we are able to demonstrate that the recent Arctic warming is also reflected in the oceanic micro-fauna. © The Author(s) 2011.","benthic foraminifera; climate change; late Holocene; Norway; palaeoceanography; stable isotopes","benthos; carbon isotope; climate change; climate modelin